Armiger

Name: Lucien Joseph Jacquet, Jr.
Place of Birth: Abington, Pennsylvania, United States
Ancestral Origin: Audincourt, France

Artist’s Description (Plain Language)
The shield is divided diagonally by a white wavy band, separating a blue upper field from a red lower field. In the upper section appear a gold scallop shell and a silver stag in motion. In the lower section appears a black anvil. Above the shield rests a steel helm with blue and green mantling, surmounted by a silver eight-pointed star. Beneath the shield is a scroll bearing the motto in French.

Symbolism Statement
The design reflects lineage, migration, labor, and continuity across generations.
The wavy diagonal band represents passage across water, signifying the migration of the Jacquet family from France to the United States in the early 20th century.
The scallop shell is a traditional emblem of journey and pilgrimage, referencing both movement and the enduring connection to French cultural and historical roots, including associations with the traditions of Saint James the Greater.
The stag symbolizes endurance, vigilance, and harmony with the natural world, reflecting both personal identity and a connection to forested and mountainous landscapes.
The anvil represents industry, labor, and the shaping of one’s circumstances through effort and persistence.
The color blue (Azure) signifies loyalty and continuity; red (Gules) signifies effort and sacrifice; white/silver (Argent) signifies clarity and transition; gold (Or) signifies enduring value; and green (Vert) in the mantling reflects growth, land, and renewal.
The eight-pointed star in the crest represents guidance, constancy, and the continuation of identity across generations.
The motto, Fidèle à ses racines, affirms a commitment to heritage while acknowledging the passage of time and place.

Compliance Statement
This armorial achievement conforms to the guidelines for American heraldic practice as outlined by the American Heraldry Society and the requirements of the U.S. Heraldic Registry:
The design consists solely of shield, helm, crest, mantling, and motto.
No elements implying nobility (such as supporters, coronets, or robes of estate) are present.
The arms are original and not derived from or duplicative of existing registered arms to the best of the armiger’s knowledge.
The blazon is expressed in standard heraldic terminology and is sufficient for reproducibility.
